---
// Problem section - pain point validation (US-003)
---

<section data-test="problem-section" id="problem" class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
  <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-8">
        Tired of Requirements That<br>
        <span class="text-red-600 dark:text-red-400">Don't Work?</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-12 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          You've been there: perfectly reasonable requirements that somehow lead to completely wrong implementations.
          The dreaded <strong>philosophy-implementation gap</strong> that kills projects.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Problem Points -->
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-16">
        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
          <div class="text-red-500 mb-4">
            <svg class="w-12 h-12 mx-auto" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-2.5L13.732 4c-.77-.833-1.964-.833-2.732 0L3.732 16.5c-.77.833.192 2.5 1.732 2.5z" />
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Spec Drift</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
            Requirements start clear but become vague over time.
            What seemed obvious to stakeholders becomes confusing to developers.
            Features ship that nobody actually wanted.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
          <div class="text-red-500 mb-4">
            <svg class="w-12 h-12 mx-auto" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M8 12h.01M12 12h.01M16 12h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Interpretation Hell</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
            Every developer reads the same requirement differently.
            Endless Slack threads debating what "user-friendly" actually means.
            Code reviews become philosophy debates.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
          <div class="text-red-500 mb-4">
            <svg class="w-12 h-12 mx-auto" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z" />
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Testing Nightmares</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
            How do you test "intuitive UX" or "scalable architecture"?
            QA teams write tests that pass but miss the real requirements.
            Bugs slip through because nobody knew what "correct" looked like.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl p-8 shadow-lg">
          <div class="text-red-500 mb-4">
            <svg class="w-12 h-12 mx-auto" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Late Discovery</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
            Critical issues discovered after months of development.
            "That's not what we meant" becomes the most expensive phrase in your vocabulary.
            Entire features get scrapped and rewritten.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Call to Action -->
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-50 to-purple-50 dark:from-blue-900/20 dark:to-purple-900/20 rounded-xl p-8">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
          There Has To Be a Better Way
        </h3>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
          What if requirements could be structured, testable, and impossible to misinterpret?
          What if your entire team could work from the same clear understanding?
        </p>
        <a
          href="#how-it-works"
          class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-700 transition-colors font-semibold"
        >
          See How RootSpec Solves This
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 ml-2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 14l-7 7m0 0l-7-7m7 7V3" />
          </svg>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>